evidence: Let’s look at a more complex example - a continuous signal that contains several frequency components.
When we add all these together, we get a signal that looks quite messy in the time domain - as you can see in the plot.
The rapid oscillations and varying amplitudes come from the interaction of all these frequencies.

That’s where the Fourier transform becomes incredibly valuable - it lets us switch to the frequency domain, where each frequency component appears as a distinct peak, making the signal’s composition much clearer.
A cosine wave at forty-five hertz
